snippet.textDisplay: Auntie Jackie, I just want to thank you for continuously educating me about the problems with the beauty industry (in terms of inclusiveness of all people and skin tones). As a young, white teenager, I have grown up in a severely segregated area of the Midwest where there aren't ANY POC in my school district. I literally only experience different cultures when I drive to the nearest city to my town. Having you as a resource has helped educate me about different cultures and struggles everybody has. I am forever grateful for your channel! You are a true inspiration and I aspire to be as outspoken as you to educate others. As I go into the beauty industry (I am going to esthetician school) I will use your tips and advice to help my future clients. Love you always 🥰😘

snippet.textDisplay: I didn't even know this was a problem... I mean im black also, my lips are a little bit darker/browner than my face and has kinda a pinkish tint underneath. So it kinda gives them a dull slightly purplish pinkish look to it that matches my face. I mean,back in old times when they made those caricatures of us they gave us massive clown lips up to our ears and made them BRIGHT BUBBLE GUM PINK and gave the person super dark skin to mock us. I always hated the stupidly pink lips and thought it made no sense. What black person has dark chocolate skin and bubble yum pink lips?? Darker lips just matches our face. One thing i found out, was I loved the way i looked in brown lipstick more than pink. It just gave me a exotic feel to my face having more chocolaty lips. So i started wearing nothing but chocolate lipstick for a while...Lol
